snippet.textDisplay:
This person is clueless. He obviously has no idea of the power of the exponential function in mathematics.

According to all best data, covid-19 has a CFR of around 3% and a R0 of 6.7. Simply put, case numbers will double every 2-3 days (if not more quickly) which means that it will take only 18 cycles, i.e. between 36 and 54 days for the virus to infect over 50 million people in the UK. Even if by some miracle case numbers doubled only every 4 days that will still mean 80% of the population will be infected by mid-May.
In Italy at present the serious complication rate is roughly 10%, meaning that 10% of those testing positive need hospitalisation. So imagine 5 million needing specialist medical care. Are there 5 million spare beds in the NHS? And enough surplus medical personnel to treat this number of patients?
Of course the answer to both questions is no.

And this is not to mention the number of deaths - at least 500,000 (assuming the CFR is only 1%), more probably 1 to 2 million. All within a space of a few months. Just think about the scale of social disruption such numbers would cause.

Seriously people, this thing will change society as we know it.

All we can do now is to prepare ourselves psychologically for the consequences because we are long past any chance of containment

Good luck to all

snippet.textDisplay: 100 thousand deaths is far too optimistic. This will spread quickly in the UK, a country that has no shortage of irresponsible, selfish people who think only of themselves. Boris Johnson's idiotic government doesn't want to ban air travel, close down schools/universities, lock-down cities, build new hospitals, invest properly in therapies or buy life-saving equipment. Even if only half the population contracts the virus, the final death toll is very likely to exceed 1 million. Most of the infected will have to fend for themselves at home without oxygen, ventilators and medicines. Any vaccine will only become available long after the general population has acquired immunity through exposure. Airports could easily have been closed by the end of January, a simple precaution that would have bought a lot of valuable time. Instead, the foolishness of the government will be directly responsible for the loss of many, many lives.
